---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  path="/research/"
  title="Research"
  description="An overview of my research — the questions, the methods, and what came out of them."
>
  <h1>Research</h1>

  <div class="prose">
    <h2>The first thread</h2>
    <p>
      This page is prose, not a list. That is the point of it: the publications
      page already says what you produced, and the CV already says where you
      were. What neither can do is explain why any of it was worth doing. A
      reader who has landed here is deciding whether to email you, and the
      thing that decides it is a clear account of a problem you find
      interesting.
    </p>
    <p>
      So write the problem first and the solution second. Say what was actually
      hard — the part that took eight months and appears in the paper as a
      single sentence in section 3.2. Name the people you worked with and
      <a href="https://example.edu">link them</a>; academia runs on those
      threads, and a reader following one is a reader who has decided you are
      real.
    </p>
    <p>
      The first paragraph of a <code>.prose</code> block opens with a drop cap.
      That is deliberate, and it is why these pages want a real opening
      sentence rather than a heading followed by a bulleted list.
    </p>

    <figure class="figure--media">
      <img
        src="/img/figure-wide.jpg"
        alt="Placeholder figure — replace with a photograph, plot, or diagram"
        width="1024"
        height="768"
        loading="lazy"
        decoding="async"
      />
      <figcaption>
        A figure sits on its own mount, the way a plate is tipped into a book.
        Captions are worth writing properly — say what is in the frame and
        when, not just what the file is called.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2>The second thread</h2>
    <p>
      Most people have more than one. Give each its own heading, keep each to
      three or four paragraphs, and put them in the order you would want to be
      asked about them rather than in chronological order.
    </p>
    <p>
      Where a paper exists, link it inline —
      <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/0000.00000">the preprint</a>, the
      published version in <cite>Journal of Relevant Things</cite>, and the
      code. A reader who wants the detail should never have to go back to the
      publications page to find it.
    </p>

    <figure class="figure--media figure--pair figure--portrait">
      <div class="figure__grid">
        <img
          src="/img/figure-tall-a.jpg"
          alt="Placeholder figure — replace or delete"
          width="768"
          height="1024"
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
        />
        <img
          src="/img/figure-tall-b.jpg"
          alt="Placeholder figure — replace or delete"
          width="768"
          height="1024"
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
        />
      </div>
      <figcaption>
        Two figures on one mount. Add <code>figure--trio</code> alongside
        <code>figure--pair</code> for three; the grid collapses to a single
        column on a narrow screen either way.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2>What you are working on now</h2>
    <p>
      Finish on the open problem rather than the finished one. It dates better,
      it is the honest answer to what you would do with more time, and it is
      the paragraph most likely to start a collaboration.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>
